1 intervene with an individual with a behavioral health condition, including a substance use
2 disorder or mental health disorder, with or without the presence of criminal activity.
3 Individual with a behavioral health condition - Assistance - Medical care .
4 A peace officer, as defined under section 12 - 63 - 01, may transport or refer an individual to a
5 local hospital, detoxification center, community behavioral health center, or other appropriate
6 treatment facility. A tier 1b mental health professional, as defined under section 25 - 01 - 01, of a
7 local hospital may hold that individual for treatment up to seventy-two hours.
8 Deflection process - Regional authority and planning.
9 1. A local government, law enforcement agency, or other first responder agency may
10 establish a deflection process in partnership with one or more licensed providers of
11 behavioral health services or substance use disorder treatment services, subject to the
12 provisions of this section. A deflection process must include participation from a law
13 enforcement agency and behavioral health service provider.
14 2. A deflection process must include procedures for:
15 a. The identification, screening, and assessment of its participants;
16 b. Case management and treatment facilitation;
17 c. Participant followups;
18 d. Law enforcement, first responder, and treatment provider training;
19 e. The collection and evaluation of data for:
20 (1) Demographics of program participants;
21 (2) The number of law enforcement interactions that result in a treatment
22 referral; and
23 (3) The time between initial law enforcement interaction and treatment service;
24 and
25 3. A deflection process must include a performance management system with key
26 performance indicators. Key performance indicators may include the:
27 a. Rate of treatment engagement within thirty days of initial contact;
28 b. Duration of treatment involvement; and
29 c. Number of subsequent law enforcement interactions for individuals referred to
30 treatment.
